# `:lsp.peek_definition_overlay` sets `pending_peek_definition = true`
# THEN calls `lsp_goto_definition`. The flag is ONLY cleared in the
# `LspEvent::GotoDefinition` handler — so if no language server is
# attached (the headless harness, OR an unsupported language, OR an
# LSP that returned a null/empty location result), the flag stays
# set indefinitely.
#
# Symptom: the NEXT `:lsp.goto_definition` call (e.g. `gd`) will be
# misrouted into the peek-overlay branch, opening a floating box
# instead of jumping the cursor.
#
# This .test verifies the "no LSP" toast path runs — the leak is
# code-readable from there.

write hello.rs "fn main() { println!(\"hi\"); }"
open hello.rs

# No LSP attached in headless. peek fires, then `lsp_goto_definition`
# toasts about no server. `pending_peek_definition` was set BEFORE
# the toast — and never cleared.
command lsp.peek_definition_overlay
# The toast appears (rendered in the statusline area) but in
# headless we can't reliably scrape it across versions. The bug is
# the FLAG STATE — the next time the LSP returns ANY GotoDefinition
# (after a real `:lsp.goto_definition` later), it'll be misrouted
# into the peek branch.
#
# We can still assert "no floating overlay opened" — load() never
# fired so peek_overlay is None. And that the editor cursor didn't
# move.
expect screen lacks "✦ peek"

# Confirm the editor is still focused at line 1.
expect pane "hello.rs"
